Certainly! Here is a list of three global initiatives contributing to the fight against poverty, formatted in JSON:

```json
{
  "global_initiatives": [
    {
      "name": "United Nations Sustainable Development Goals",
      "goal": "End poverty in all its forms everywhere by 2030",
      "description": "A collection of 17 interlinked global goals designed to be a blueprint to achieve a better and more sustainable future for all."
    },
    {
      "name": "World Bank Group's Poverty Reduction Strategy",
      "goal": "Reduce the percentage of people living on less than $1.25 a day to 3% by 2030",
      "description": "Focuses on promoting shared prosperity through inclusive economic growth, investing in people, and building resilience to shocks and threats."
    },
    {
      "name": "Oxfam International",
      "goal": "Tackle the root causes of poverty and create lasting solutions",
      "description": "An international confederation of NGOs working together to alleviate global poverty through advocacy, development programs, and emergency response."
    }
  ]
}
```

These initiatives represent collaborative efforts from various organizations aimed at reducing poverty on a global scale.
